definition:
The *complete bipartite graph* $K_{n,m}$ is a graph with two sets of
vertices, one with $n$ members and one with $m$, such that each vertex
in one set is adjacent to every vertex in the other set and to no vertex
in its own set. As the name implies, $K_{n,m}$ is bipartite.

Examples of complete bipartite graphs:

$K_{2,5}$:

$$\xymatrix{
  & C \\
A \ar@{-}[ur] \ar@{-}[r] \ar@{-}[dr] \ar@{-}[ddr] \ar@{-}[dddr] & D \\
  & E \\
B \ar@{-}[uuur] \ar@{-}[uur] \ar@{-}[ur] \ar@{-}[r] \ar@{-}[dr] & F \\
  & G
}$$

$K_{3,3}$:

$$\xymatrix{
A \ar@{-}[r] \ar@{-}[dr] \ar@{-}[ddr] & D \\
B \ar@{-}[ur] \ar@{-}[r] \ar@{-}[dr] & E \\
C \ar@{-}[uur] \ar@{-}[ur] \ar@{-}[r] & F 
}$$
